Personally, I wouldn't bother with a decoction.  It's a lot of extra
work and there's really not much benefit.  Note also that I believe
Noonan has come out and said (after the book was written) that he probably
wouldn't recommend it anymore either because of the quality of grains we
have available today.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; At the end of ch-14, he provides several simple recipes for lager
&gt; styles. Now, in these recipes (e.g. the Munich dark) he states:

&gt; Doughing-in: 8 quarts
&gt; Mashing-in: 5 quarts
&gt; Strike Temp: 155F

&gt; What are the water quantities for? Are they quantities of boiling water
&gt; to be used for a step/infusion mash?
">

I think those are just the volume of the initial strike water.  IE, both
are added before the real mash begins.  It looks kind of strange to
list them seperately like that, but I think that's what he meant.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; This is probably a silly question, but I just want to be clear on
&gt; it. Since he leaves infusion mashes for the appendices, I'm confused
&gt; by the appearance of these numbers in the recipes.
">

I don't think "Doughing-in" and "Mashing-in" are seperate infusion steps.
It think he's just breaking the initial water into two categories.

John.
